=============================
| Lambda Function in Python |
=============================
Lambda Function is a small anonymous function in Python that can have any number of arguments, but only one expression. 
It is created using the lambda keyword and returns the result of the expression automatically.

A lambda function is an anonymous (nameless) function used for writing short, one-line functions.

Syntax
  lambda arguments: expression

Arguments
     │
     ▼
Expression Execute
     │
     ▼
Result Automatically Return

square = lambda x: x * x
print(square(5))
O/P : 25

add = lambda a, b: a + b
print(add(10, 20))
O/P : 30

upper = lambda name: name.upper()
print(upper("hello"))
O/P : HELLO

is_even = lambda n: n % 2 == 0

print(is_even(8))
print(is_even(5))
O/P True
    False


=============================
| Lambda vs Normal Function |
=============================
def square(x):
    return x * x
print(square(5))   O/P : 5
_____________________________

square = lambda x: x * x
print(square(5))    O/P : 5
_____________________________

greater = lambda a, b: a if a > b else b
print(greater(15, 30))
O/P : 30
_____________________________

total = lambda a, b, c: a + b + c
print(total(10, 20, 30))
O/P : 60

============================
| map() Function in Python |
============================
👉 map() is a built-in Python function that applies a given function to every item of an iterable (such as a list, tuple, or set) 
   and returns a map object containing the transformed values.

👉 The map() function applies a function to each element of an iterable and returns the modified results.

# map() Built-in Python function

map(function, iterable)   

How map() Works
List
 │
 ▼
Take First Element
 │
 ▼
Apply Function
 │
 ▼
Store Result
 │
 ▼
Take Second Element
 │
 ▼
Apply Function
 │
 ▼
Store Result
 │
 ▼
Continue until end

Example 1 (Using Normal Function)
    def square(x):
        return x * x
    numbers = [1, 2, 3, 4]
    result = map(square, numbers)
    print(result)

Example 2 (Using Lambda)
    numbers = [1, 2, 3, 4]
    result = map(lambda x: x * x, numbers)
    print(list(result))

O/P : [1, 4, 9, 16]

Example 3 (Add 10)
    numbers = [5, 10, 15, 20]
    result = map(lambda x: x + 10, numbers)
    print(list(result))

O/P : [15, 20, 25, 30]

Example 4 (Convert into Uppercase)
    names = ["mridul", "aman", "rohan"]
    result = map(lambda name: name.upper(), names)
    print(list(result))

O/P : ['MRIDUL', 'AMAN', 'ROHAN']

Example 5 (Length of Strings)
    names = ["Python", "Java", "AI"]
    result = map(len, names)
    print(list(result))

O/P : [6, 4, 2]

Example 6 (Multiple Iterables)
    a = [1, 2, 3]
    b = [10, 20, 30]
    result = map(lambda x, y: x + y, a, b)
    print(list(result))

O/P : [11, 22, 33]


